<PROGRAM_THEORY: THE_MEMEX_TEST>

<Initial Interpretation>
  <paper> := <knowledge-infrastructure diagnostic>
  <problem> := <civilization> has produced <records> faster than <scholars> can consult, connect, inherit, or judge them.
  <real_activity> := <scholarship> as [trail-making
] through <archives>, not [answer-extraction
] from <databases>.
  <central_intervention> :=
    <AI-assisted scholarship> must be judged by <path integrity>, not by <answer fluency>.

  <governing_question>
    Can a system show not only <what it says>, but <how its path through the record was built>?
  </governing_question>

  <thesis>
    <Bush's memex> is not mainly a prophecy of hypertext.
    It is a theory of <auditable intellectual traversal>.
    The <trail> is the missing ethical object in contemporary AI scholarship.
  </thesis>


<Theory Skeleton>
  <entities>
    <record>
    <archive>
    <scholar>
    <reader>
    <machine>
    <memex>
    <trail>
    <index>
    <association>
    <source>
    <citation>
    <annotation>
    <branch>
    <evidence>
    <judgment>
    <provenance>
    <retrieval>
    <generation>
    <answer>
    <scaffold>
    <AI-system>
    <knowledge-overload>
    <pathlessness>
    <memex-test>
  </entities>

  [operations
]
    [record
]
    [store
]
    [consult
]
    [select
]
    [retrieve
]
    [link
]
    [associate
]
    [annotate
]
    [branch
]
    [summarize
]
    [generate
]
    [cite
]
    [compress
]
    [audit
]
    [contest
]
    [inherit
]
    [teach
]
    [revise
]
    [preserve
]
    [make-visible
]
  [/operations
]

  <states>
    <stored>
    <unconsulted>
    <selected>
    <linked>
    <trailed>
    <annotated>
    <branched>
    <compressed>
    <generated>
    <cited>
    <plausible>
    <opaque>
    <auditable>
    <inheritable>
    <pathless>
    <accountable>
  </states>

  <constraints>
    <storage> != <knowledge>
    <retrieval> != <interpretation>
    <citation> != <provenance>
    <summary> != <understanding>
    <link> != <trail>
    <answer> != <scholarly account>
    <fluency> != <judgment>
  </constraints>

  <invariants>
    I1: <scholarly claim> requires <inspectable evidence path>.
    I2: <trail> must preserve <sequence>, <selection>, <association>, <annotation>, and <branch>.
    I3: <AI assistance> becomes <delegation> when <path> disappears.
    I4: <augmentation> preserves <human relation to evidence>.
    I5: <knowledge system> fails when it produces <answers> without <recoverable scaffolds>.
    I6: <memex-test> evaluates <path integrity>, not <output polish>.
  </invariants>


<Assumption Ledger>
  <safe>
    <Bush> is read as a theorist of <knowledge overload>, <selection>, and <associative traversal>.
  </safe>

  <safe>
    <memex> is defined by <trail-making>, not by <microfilm storage>.
  </safe>

  <safe>
    <AI scholarship tools> intensify Bush's problem by producing <synthesis> without necessarily preserving <provenance>.
  </safe>

  <uncertain>
    <visible trails> may slow users down; the paper assumes this friction is epistemically valuable when scholarship is the goal.
  </uncertain>

  <uncertain>
    Different <AI systems> may expose different layers of <path>; the test must be adaptable.
  </uncertain>

  <requires-user-decision>
    Whether final form is <dissertation chapter>, <journal article>, <design manifesto>, or <AI ethics framework>.
  </requires-user-decision>


<Operational Description>
  <civilization> [produces
] <expanding record>
  <expanding record> [creates
] <knowledge-overload>
  <knowledge-overload> [exposes
] <consultation crisis>
  <consultation crisis> [requires
] <selection system>

  <index> [files
] <record> by <fixed class>
  <association> [moves
] <reader> by <felt relevance>
  <memex> [mechanizes
] <association>
  <scholar> [builds
] <trail>
  <trail> [preserves
] <path of judgment>

  <AI-system> [retrieves
] <sources>
  <AI-system> [generates
] <answer>
  <answer> [appears-as
] <synthesis>
  <synthesis> [fails-if
] <path> is hidden

  <memex-test> [asks
] <AI-system>:
    show <question>
    show <query transformations>
    show <source field>
    show <selected sources>
    show <discarded sources>
    show <associations>
    show <annotations>
    show <branches>
    show <uncertainties>
    show <final claim>

  <condition: path-visible>
    [enables
] <accountable scholarship>
  </condition>

  <condition: path-hidden>
    [produces
] <opaque synthesis>
    [blocks
] <scholarly inheritance>
  </condition>


<Failure Description>
  <failure: STORAGE_CONFUSION>
    <system> [treats
] <more stored records> as <more knowledge>.
    <correction> Reassert <consultation> as the real bottleneck.
  </failure>

  <failure: RETRIEVAL_CONFUSION>
    <system> [treats
] <found source> as <interpreted evidence>.
    <correction> Require <selection rationale> and <argumentative role>.
  </failure>

  <failure: CITATION_THEATER>
    <answer> [contains
] <citations> but [hides
] <source path>.
    <correction> Demand <provenance>, not citation garnish.
  </failure>

  <failure: LINK_COLLAPSE>
    <trail> [collapses into
] <hyperlink>.
    <correction> Restore <sequence>, <branch>, <annotation>, and <use-history>.
  </failure>

  <failure: OPAQUE_SYNTHESIS>
    <AI-system> [outputs
] <fluent prose> without <auditable route>.
    <correction> Mark as <pathless>; fail <memex-test>.
  </failure>

  <failure: DELEGATED_JUDGMENT>
    <scholar> [receives
] <answer> without [learning
] <field traversal>.
    <correction> Rebuild tool as <augmentation>, not replacement.
  </failure>


<Change Test>
  <scenario: journal_article>
    <change>
      Compress <historical genealogy>.
      Move <memex-test> earlier.
      Sharpen <AI critique>.
    </change>
  </scenario>

  <scenario: dissertation_chapter>
    <change>
      Expand <Bush close reading>.
      Add <Otlet>, <Wells>, <Engelbart>, <Nelson>, <Web>, <RAG>.
      Build fuller <media archaeology>.
    </change>
  </scenario>

  <scenario: design_manifesto>
    <change>
      Convert <memex-test> into <interface requirements>.
      Add <trail UI>, <source map>, <branch history>, <audit panel>.
    </change>
  </scenario>

  <scenario: AI_ethics_framework>
    <change>
      Foreground <provenance>, <pedagogy>, <citation integrity>, <institutional accountability>.
    </change>
  </scenario>


<Implementation Plan>
  <section_1: After the War, the Record>
    [frame
] <Bush> as postwar theorist of <knowledge infrastructure>.
  </section_1>

  <section_2: Storage Is Not Enough>
    [distinguish
] <storage> from <consultation>.
  </section_2>

  <section_3: Repetitive Thought and Mature Judgment>
    [separate
] <mechanizable operation> from <interpretive judgment>.
  </section_3>

  <section_4: Against Indexing>
    [oppose
] <artificial classification> to <associative movement>.
  </section_4>

  <section_5: Trail as Scholarly Form>
    [define
] <trail> as <visible scaffold of inquiry>.
  </section_5>

  <section_6: From Memex to Hypertext to AI>
    [trace
] <memex> -> <hypertext> -> <web> -> <AI retrieval/generation>.
  </section_6>

  <section_7: Provenance Against Plausibility>
    [argue
] <plausible answer> without <path> is epistemically weak.
  </section_7>

  <section_8: The Memex Test>
    [formalize
] <criterion> for scholarly AI.
  </section_8>

  <section_9: Trail Blazers>
    [recast
] <scholar> as <builder of inheritable paths>.
  </section_9>

  <section_10: Conclusion>
    [assert
] <future scholarly AI> must preserve <trail integrity>.
  </section_10>


<Program Text>
  <paper_program>
    INPUT:
      <Bush_1945>
      <postwar_science>
      <knowledge_overload>
      <memex>
      <hypertext_lineage>
      <AI_assisted_scholarship>

    PROCESS:
      1. [read
] <Bush> as <knowledge-infrastructure theorist>
      2. [extract
] <problem>: <record abundance> exceeds <consultation capacity>
      3. [reject
] <storage solutionism>
      4. [identify
] <selection> as <prime action of use>
      5. [define
] <trail> as <associative path through evidence>
      6. [contrast
] <trail> with <index>, <link>, <citation>, <summary>
      7. [map
] <memex lineage> onto <AI scholarship tools>
      8. [diagnose
] <AI answer fluency> as insufficient without <path>
      9. [formulate
] <memex-test>
      10. [intervene
] by demanding <auditable scholarly AI>

    OUTPUT:
      <argument>
        <AI-assisted scholarship> is ethical only when it preserves the
        <visible, revisable, inheritable trail> by which <answers> are made.
      </argument>

      <test>
        A system passes the <memex-test> only if another scholar can follow,
        inspect, contest, revise, and inherit its route through the record.
      </test>
  </paper_program>


<Theory-Code Mapping>
  <types>
    <record>, <trail>, <source>, <annotation>, <branch>, <AI-system>, <answer>, <provenance>
    function as the paper's core conceptual data structures.
  </types>

  <functions>
    [select
],
[associate
],
[annotate
],
[branch
],
[retrieve
],
[generate
],
[audit
]
    function as the paper's main operations.
  </functions>

  <classes>
    <memex> := class of tools that preserve <associative trails>.
    <AI-system> := class of tools that may retrieve/generate but must be tested for <path visibility>.
    <scholar> := actor responsible for <judgment>, <association>, and <accountability>.
  </classes>

  <tests>
    <memex-test> :=
      IF <system> shows <answer> AND <path>
      THEN <system> supports <scholarly augmentation>
      ELSE <system> produces <opaque synthesis>.
  </tests>

  <comments>
    <citation theater>, <opaque synthesis>, <retrieval confusion>, and <trail collapse>
    are not side issues; they are structural failures of scholarly infrastructure.
  </comments>

  <configuration>
    output_mode: <dissertation chapter>
    density: <dense>
    realism_mode: <hybrid>
    abstraction_level: <high>
    intervention_pressure: <high>
  </configuration>


<Residual Human Theory>
  <uncaptured>
    The code-form cannot fully capture the historical pressure of 1945:
    <science> emerging from <war>, seeking a non-destructive task equal to its power.
  </uncaptured>

  <maintainer_warning>
    Do not reduce <trail> to <link>.
    Do not reduce <provenance> to <citation>.
    Do not reduce <scholarship> to <answer production>.
    Do not let <AI fluency> impersonate <judgment>.
  </maintainer_warning>

  <survival_rule>
    The paper survives revision only if this remains true:
    <scholarly knowledge> requires <visible paths of selection, association, evidence, and judgment>.
  </survival_rule>

</PROGRAM_THEORY>